 {"id":"flywheel_gateway-dkz","title":"[Epic] Rate Limit Headers","description":"# Epic: Rate Limit Headers

## Background & Problem Statement
The API has rate limiting capabilities but doesn't communicate rate limit status to clients via standard HTTP headers. Clients can't proactively manage their request rate.

### Current State Analysis
- Rate limiting exists (RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED error code in taxonomy)
- No rate limit headers returned in responses
- Clients only learn about limits when they hit them
- No way to see remaining quota

### Industry Standard (Stripe/GitHub)
Rate limit headers in every response:
```
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
X-RateLimit-Limit: 100
X-RateLimit-Remaining: 99
X-RateLimit-Reset: 1620000000
```

On rate limit exceeded:
```
HTTP/1.1 429 Too Many Requests
X-RateLimit-Limit: 100
X-RateLimit-Remaining: 0
X-RateLimit-Reset: 1620000060
Retry-After: 60
```

### Why This Matters
1. **Proactive Throttling**: Clients can slow down before hitting limits
2. **Efficient Scheduling**: Batch operations when quota available
3. **Debugging**: Understand why requests failed
4. **Multi-Client Coordination**: Shared quota visibility

## Goals
1. **Visibility**: Every response includes rate limit headers
2. **Predictability**: Clients know when limits reset
3. **Graceful Handling**: 429 includes Retry-After
4. **Granularity**: Per-endpoint or per-resource limits visible

## Success Criteria
- [ ] Rate limit tracking middleware created
- [ ] All responses include rate limit headers
- [ ] 429 responses include Retry-After
- [ ] Rate limits configurable per endpoint
- [ ] Tests verify header presence
- [ ] Documentation explains rate limits

## Technical Approach
1. Create rate limit tracking middleware
2. Store request counts (in-memory or Redis)
3. Add headers via Hono middleware
4. Configure limits per endpoint/resource
5. Return 429 with proper headers when exceeded

## Header Definitions
- `X-RateLimit-Limit`: Maximum requests allowed in window
- `X-RateLimit-Remaining`: Requests remaining in window
- `X-RateLimit-Reset`: Unix timestamp when window resets
- `Retry-After`: Seconds until retry allowed (on 429)

## Rate Limit Strategies
1. **Per-IP**: Simple but problematic with shared IPs
2. **Per-API-Key**: Standard for authenticated APIs
3. **Per-User**: Based on authenticated user
4. **Per-Resource**: Limits on specific resources (agent creation)

## Window Types
- **Fixed Window**: Reset at fixed intervals (simple but bursty)
- **Sliding Window**: Rolling window (smoother but complex)
- **Token Bucket**: Burst-friendly with sustained limit

## Dependencies
- None directly, can be done independently

## Risks & Mitigations
- **Performance**: Tracking requests adds overhead
  - Mitigation: Use efficient in-memory counter with atomic ops
- **Distributed**: Multiple instances need shared state
  - Mitigation: Redis for distributed rate limiting
- **Clock Skew**: Reset times may vary
  - Mitigation: Use relative Retry-After in addition to Reset","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-01-11T10:01:33.181796193-05:00","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-01-12T19:31:00.044247275-05:00","closed_at":"2026-01-12T19:31:00.044247275-05:00","close_reason":"Already implemented: apps/gateway/src/middleware/rate-limit.ts has full X-RateLimit-* and Retry-After header support. Tests in rate-limit.middleware.test.ts verify functionality. Documentation exists in docs/api-guide.md."}
